    <h1>Non-circular detection of shortcut reliance</h1>
    <p class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)] italic !text-lg !mb-8">
      Separating stipulated causal irrelevance from measured training entanglement.
    </p>

    <h2>The problem this version set out to solve</h2>
    <p>
      Perturbation- and robustness-based evaluations ask whether a correct answer survives a
      meaning-preserving change. They share an unstated circularity: deciding which perturbations
      <em>should</em> leave the answer unchanged already presupposes the causal structure being
      tested. Calling a variable "irrelevant" requires the very knowledge whose use by the model is in
      question.
    </p>

    <h2>The move</h2>
    <p>
      The circular question — "is variable <code>Z</code> irrelevant to conclusion <code>C</code>?" —
      conflates two facts of different epistemic status:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Causal irrelevance</strong>, a fact about the task — fixed non-circularly <em>by construction</em>, since we author the synthetic item and stipulate its ground-truth graph.</li>
      <li><strong>Training entanglement</strong>, a fact about the data — fixed non-circularly <em>by measurement</em>, as a label correlation on an auditable corpus that needs no causal assumption.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      A legitimate shortcut-detection target is exactly a variable that is causally irrelevant by
      construction <strong>and</strong> training-correlated by measurement.
    </p>

    <h2>The disciplined package</h2>
    <p>
      Neither half is individually new; the contribution is the discipline that the split forces:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>a <strong>class-1/2/3 taxonomy</strong> of variables that the construction/measurement split implies;</li>
      <li>a <strong>mandatory class-2 control</strong> (a matched pure-noise intervention) that rules out the trivial reading "any intervention breaks the model";</li>
      <li>a <strong>boundary discipline</strong> confining the causal machinery to settings where the graph is stipulated and the training data auditable.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>What it showed</h2>
    <p>
      Across three model classes spanning the main families of learned sequence models — TF-IDF +
      logistic regression, fine-tuned DistilBERT (66M), and LoRA-fine-tuned Qwen2.5-1.5B — the
      procedure is <strong>specific</strong> (it does not flag a model that genuinely uses the
      stipulated structure), <strong>sensitive</strong> (it flags a shortcut-rider), and
      <strong>non-vacuous</strong> (the pure-noise control stays intact).
    </p>
    <p>
      Under training-seed variance the sensitivity arm is fully stable (5/5). The multi-premise
      specificity arm did <em>not</em> return a clean pass: it surfaced a premise-use asymmetry — the
      model leans on one premise more than requiring both. That is a diagnostic the procedure is
      designed to expose, reported rather than smoothed over. A complementary measurement-only section
      illustrated, on BoolQ across three zero-shot models, that headline accuracy can substantially
      overstate the fraction of <em>stably</em>-correct items.
    </p>

    <h2>Why it became v2</h2>
    <p>
      v1 delivered the non-circular procedure but framed it as an evaluation-methodology contribution
      sitting beside a separate accuracy-vs-stability observation. The next version unified them:
      the procedure is one cut in a strict hierarchy, and the place where that cut is cleanest is
      named in advance by grammar.
    </p>

